<p class="newssubhead_t1">Keith Good Farm Policy: USDA Predicts 20 Percent Jump in Net-Farm Income</p>
By Keith Good<br />
Agricultural Economy<br />
<br />
Bloomberg writer Alan Bjerga reported yesterday that, &ldquo;U.S. farmers are less optimistic about their current and future economic situation than they were in December, according to a survey-based index produced by DTN/The Progressive Farmer.<br />
<br />
&ldquo;Farmers gave their present economic circumstances an index score of 111, down from 151 in December, with 100 indicating sentiment in the benchmark month of April 2010, the agricultural news service said today. The April survey was the first conducted by the unit of Madrid-based Telvent GIT SA. Growers gave a rating of 91 for their outlook for the economy one year from now, down from 117 in December.<br />
<br />
&ldquo;The U.S. Department of Agriculture is predicting a 20 percent jump in net-farm income this year to a record $94.7 billion. Farm exports will jump 25 percent to $135.5 billion in fiscal 2011, the highest ever, the USDA said last month. Still, higher oil prices and possible economic disruption related to Japan&rsquo;s earthquake have pushed prices for corn, wheat and soybeans traded in Chicago down at least 6.1 percent from last month&rsquo;s highs for the year.&rdquo;<br />
<br />
Meanwhile, Marcia Zarley Taylor reported yesterday at the DTN Minding Ag&rsquo;s Business Blog that, &ldquo;News last week that Illinois Society of Farm Managers and Rural Appraisers recorded more rallies in the state&rsquo;s land values for 2010 shouldn&rsquo;t surprise anyone. After all, in the last four months, farmland in Illinois rose by as much as $1,500 an acre, reports Jeff Waddell, president of the real estate firm of Martin Goodrich &amp; Wadell, in Sycamore, Ill. He&rsquo;s seeing more high-quality farmland bring $9,000 to $10,500 throughout the state, not that much different than the recession-adjusted prices for land suitable for development. The big problem, Waddell adds, is that in this seller&rsquo;s market, Class A farmland listings are virtually nonexistent.<br />
<br />
&ldquo;Land is appreciating so fast that even professional appraisers have misgauged the market. Charles Knudson, 1st Farm Credit Services, says the last piece of good quality farmland around Bloomington sold for $11,500/acre in early March, up $3,000 to $3,500 from a year earlier. In September, he appraised a property at $8,100/acre for an interested buyer, but it sold at auction in February for $10,150/acre.<br />
<br />
&ldquo;At the moment farmland is appreciating at the fastest clip since the 1970s, Knudson adds. Just between August and March, it&rsquo;s up 4 percent per month. &lsquo;Back in the 1970s, we went from $800 to $4,000 per acre in six years. Going from $6,500 to $11,150 isn&rsquo;t quite the same rate of appreciation, but the dollar values are bigger.&rsquo;&rdquo;<br />
<br />
<br />
