Regulations<br />
<br />
Todd Neeley reported yesterday at DTN (link requires subscription) that, &ldquo;A group of agriculture chemical companies is trying to intervene in a lawsuit filed against EPA that could have far-reaching effects on the way U.S. farmers do business.<br />
<br />
&ldquo;CropLife America, leading the group, made a motion to intervene on March 18, according to court documents filed in the U.S. District Court California Northern District.<br />
<br />
&ldquo;In addition, a coalition of agriculture commodity groups is planning to mount a challenge in the case as well.&rdquo;<br />
<br />
The DTN article stated that, &ldquo;&lsquo;AFBF is also planning to move for intervention in the case,&rsquo; said Ellen Steen, general counsel and secretary for the American Farm Bureau Federation. &lsquo;We are working with other grower groups and we hope to file a joint motion for leave to intervene in the near future.&rsquo;<br />
<br />
&ldquo;EPA and two environmental groups recently received the green light from the court to work out a settlement in a lawsuit that agricultural groups and pesticide experts have said could stop or strictly limit the use of ag chemicals.<br />
<br />
&ldquo;On Jan. 20, the Center for Biological Diversity and Pesticide Action Network North America alleged in a lawsuit that EPA violated the Endangered Species Act by not consulting federal wildlife officials about the potential effects that registered pesticides and other agriculture chemicals would have on hundreds of species.&rdquo;<br />
<br />
Mr. Neeley explained that, &ldquo;All of the parties indicated in court documents that they may reach a settlement and were granted an additional 90 days in which to do so.<br />
<br />
&ldquo;In recent weeks, members of Congress have questioned EPA Administrator Lisa Jackson about the agency&rsquo;s seeming willingness to settle rather than challenge lawsuits. The Center for Biological Diversity has a long history of filing suits against EPA and forcing settlements.<br />
<br />
&ldquo;CropLife America et al, argue in their motion that their best interests would not be represented in the case.&rdquo;<br />
<br />
A news release yesterday from EPA stated that, &ldquo;U.S. Environmental Protection Agency Administrator Lisa P. Jackson will make a long-planned visit to California this week, where she will meet with state and local agriculture and business leaders. Having just returned from Brazil, where she traveled with President Obama and other members of the president&rsquo;s Cabinet, Administrator Jackson&rsquo;s two-and-half-day California trip will include stops in Los Angeles and Fresno&hellip;[A]dministrator Jackson will also spend a full day in Fresno, where she will visit farms, meet with agricultural leaders, hold discussions with Fresno Mayor Ashley Swearengin and meet with local environmental justice activists.&rdquo;<br />
<br />
Meanwhile, in a letter to President Obama on Friday, several GOP Governors noted that, &ldquo;The uncertainties caused by international events that are well beyond the Administration&rsquo;s control are further compounded by the unreasonably aggressive regulatory agenda being pursued by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA). As the stewards of our states&rsquo; natural resources, we share the broad goals of the EPA to protect our air and water. However, we wish to express our strong concerns over the contents and timing of many of the recently adopted and pending regulations, which together could seriously impact energy supply, reliability, and affordability for the residents, small businesses, and manufacturers in our states and across the country.&rdquo;<br />
<br />
The letter added that, &ldquo;We request that you ensure any EPA rule maintains the partnership between the federal government and the states; allows for a full analysis of the costs and benefits of the proposed regulations on the economy, jobs and American economic competitiveness; and ensures that new rules do not increase the already high cost of energy to American consumers. We further request that EPA, in partnership with state regulators, analyze and make available cost estimates to states for implementing new regulations.&rdquo;<br />
<br />
With respect to greenhouse gas regulation, the &ldquo;Washington Insider&rdquo; section of DTN reported yesterday (link requires subscription) that, &ldquo;Senate Minority Leader Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., had hoped to bring to the floor last week his proposal to throttle the Environmental Protection Agency&rsquo;s authority to regulate greenhouse gas emissions. However, he was thwarted when it became apparent that the proposal did not have the 60 votes it would need to pass. With both houses of Congress now on a week-long recess until March 28, McConnell&rsquo;s legislation will not be considered until late March at the earliest.<br />
<br />
&ldquo;The minority leader&rsquo;s proposal is in the form of an amendment to the Small Business Reauthorization Act that would end all EPA authority to address emissions related to global climate change and block all current and future emissions rules.<br />
<br />
&ldquo;Senate Finance Chairman Max Baucus, D-Mont., says there may be several more anti-EPA amendments offered to the small business bill, including one by Baucus himself that would exempt the agricultural sector from EPA&rsquo;s greenhouse gas rules and shield small business from its greenhouse gas rules governing power plants and other stationary sources.&rdquo;<br />
<br />
From a state perspective, Margot Roosevelt reported yesterday at the Los Angeles Times Online that, &ldquo;A San Francisco superior court judge has put California&rsquo;s sweeping plan to curb greenhouse gas pollution on hold, saying the state did not adequately evaluate alternatives to its cap-and-trade program.<br />
<br />
&ldquo;In a 35-page decision, Judge Ernest H. Goldsmith said the Air Resources Board had failed to consider public comments on the proposed measures before adopting the plan, which affects a broad swath of the state&rsquo;s economy.&rdquo;<br />
