Budget: Farm Bill<br />
<br />
Tom Steever reported yesterday at Brownfield that, &ldquo;Senate Agriculture Committee member John Thune says bi-partisan support for government farm programs has deteriorated since the last farm bill. The South Dakota Republican says people believe the current farm economy has resulted in less necessity for a federal farm program, but he says there needs to be a foundation supporting agriculture when commodity prices come back down.<br />
<br />
&ldquo;&lsquo;Part of it, I think, is just going to be winning the argument this year with the people in Congress that we need to continue to provide support for American agriculture,&rsquo; Senator Thune told Brownfield in Washington.&rdquo;<br />
<br />
Yesterday&rsquo;s update noted that, &ldquo;Additionally, Thune points out that much of the cost of federal farm policy no longer supports farmers.<br />
<br />
&ldquo;&lsquo;People forget that only about 12 percent of the entire ag budget actually supports production agriculture,&rsquo; said Senator Thune. &lsquo;Most of it goes to other nutrition programs, assistance programs, those sorts of things, so it&rsquo;s a very, very small amount of the agricultural budget in this country [that] actually is about production agriculture.&rsquo;&rdquo;<br />
<br />
Meanwhile, yesterday&rsquo;s &ldquo;Agriculture Today&rdquo; radio program on the Red River Farm Network (RRFN) featured an interview with House Agriculture Committee Ranking Member Collin Peterson (D-Minn.).  Rep. Petersonheld a meeting yesterday with agricultural stakeholders in Ada, Minnesota.  During the RRFN radio interview, Rep. Peterson discussed the federal budget, and Farm Bill issues- just click here to listen (MP3- 2:34).<br />
<br />
A news release yesterday from Senate Agriculture Committee Chairwoman Debbie Stabenow (D- Michigan) stated that, &ldquo;[Senator Stabenow], today met with Michigan grain and feed producers in Albion. She also toured The Andersons Albion biofuels facility-a 55 million gallon dry mill fuel facility which employs 38 workers. The facility produces 155,000 tons of dried distiller grains annually, which provides a high quality feed for livestock in Michigan and across the region.<br />
<br />
Senator Debbie Stabenow said: &lsquo;Our grain and feed producers are playing a critical role in creating new jobs at a time when nothing is more important than growing the economy. Our ag producers are engaged in cutting edge innovation, developing new opportunities in domestic energy production and expanding feed and grain exports. There&rsquo;s a reason why Michigan&rsquo;s agricultural economy continues to grow five times faster than the general economy, and I&rsquo;m seeing it here today in Albion.&rsquo;<br />
<br />
&ldquo;Hal Reed, President of The Andersons Grain and Ethanol Group and President of the National Grain and Feed Association said: &lsquo;The Andersons was honored to host Senator Stabenow for a conversation with local grain and feed producers today. We believe it is important to facilitate discussions regarding such important agricultural issues as the farm bill, the conservation reserve program, biofuels policy, and trade policy between the farming community, businesses and governmental leadership. We appreciate the Senator&rsquo;s advocacy for agribusiness in Michigan.&rsquo;&rdquo;<br />
<br />
A news release Friday from Rep. Roscoe Bartlett (R- Maryland) stated in part that, &ldquo;[Congressman Bartlett] hosted more than a hundred constituents at a Farmers and Growers Town Hall meeting on Friday, March 18th&hellip;Congressman Bartlett also provided attendees at his Town Hall with a preview of the next Farm Bill anticipated to be approved during this Congress because the current Farm bill expires in 2012.  Congressman Bartlett noted, &lsquo;The Farm bill authorizes most federal farm and food policies.  While we face over a trillion dollar budget deficit in FY2012, developing the next farm bill will be a challenge.  The total cost of the 2008 Farm Bill as enacted was $283 billion.  Congress must establish clear priorities to ensure that we can maintain the high levels of food production that we and the rest of the world demands.  In order to set the priorities correctly, I need the input from my farm constituents to share with my colleagues on the Agriculture Committee who will be doing the bulk of this work.&rsquo;&rdquo;<br />
<br />
And a news release Friday from Maurice Hinchey (D-New York) indicated that, &ldquo;Bob Franklin is a small family farmer in Swan Lake, New York who bottles his own milk and produces other agricultural products for sale in local and regional markets. With large, corporate-run agribusinesses dominating today&rsquo;s agricultural marketplace, it&rsquo;s a story that&rsquo;s becoming less and less common in Sullivan County as Upstate&rsquo;s small farming community struggles to hang on. [Congressman Hinchey] visited the farm today to learn about the unique products that Bob is offering and discuss ways in which federal policy can help boost small farmers and make it easier to raise a family on a farm-based income.&rdquo;<br />
<br />
The release added that, &ldquo;As Congress begins debate over the next Farm Bill, Hinchey says there are several provisions that can be included to help area farmers, including provisions to provide better access to capital and address the dairy crisis. Hinchey also expressed his support for efforts to obtain a U.S. Department of Agriculture Rural Business Enterprise Grant that would help build a small dairy processing facility for Sullivan County dairy farmers. Today&rsquo;s visit, however, was an opportunity to listen and learn about an innovative approach that&rsquo;s already proven successful.
